---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Nav from '../components/Nav.astro';
import StatusStrip from '../components/StatusStrip.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Nan Madol — A Lost City in the Sea | Pohnpei Island"
  description="Nan Madol is a UNESCO World Heritage Site off the southeast coast of Pohnpei — 92 artificial islets of stacked basalt built between 1180 and 1628 CE. Here's how to visit."
>
  <Nav />
  <StatusStrip />

  <main class="pt-[116px]">

    <!-- 1. HERO -->
    <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-basalt">
      <div class="relative aspect-[16/9] md:aspect-[21/9] min-h-[480px] md:min-h-[560px]">
        <img
          class="w-full h-full object-cover opacity-60"
          src="https://res.cloudinary.com/doruy2kdr/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,c_fill,g_auto,w_2000,h_900/feature-nan-madol-step-into.jpg"
          alt="Nan Madol — basalt ruins rising from the lagoon"
        />
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-t from-basalt/80 via-basalt/30 to-transparent"></div>
        <div class="absolute inset-0 flex flex-col justify-end p-6 md:p-16 lg:p-24 max-w-4xl">
          <span
            class="font-label text-ochre tracking-[0.3em] uppercase text-[11px] font-semibold mb-4 block"
          >
            A UNESCO World Heritage Site
          </span>
          <h1
            class="font-headline text-sand text-5xl md:text-6xl lg:text-7xl leading-[1.02] tracking-tight mb-3"
          >
            Nan Madol
          </h1>
          <p class="font-headline text-sand/80 text-2xl md:text-3xl italic mb-8">
            A lost city <em class="text-ochre">in the sea</em>.
          </p>
          <div>
            <a
              href="/plan-your-trip"
              class="bg-ochre text-white px-8 py-4 font-label uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-xs font-semibold hover:bg-ochre-deep active:scale-95 transition-all inline-block"
            >
              Plan your visit →
            </a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. WHAT IT IS -->
    <section class="py-20 md:py-28 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto reveal">
        <p class="font-body text-basalt/80 text-lg md:text-xl leading-relaxed">
          92 artificial islets, built of stacked basalt logs, set across a lagoon
          off the southeast coast of Pohnpei. Construction began around 1180 CE
          and continued for more than 400 years. It's the only ancient city on
          Earth built on a coral reef — and the only UNESCO World Heritage Site
          in Micronesia.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 3. AMONG THE WORLD'S WONDERS -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand-bright tapa-pattern">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-10"
        >
          Built at the same time as <em class="italic text-ochre">Machu Picchu</em>.
        </h2>

        <div class="reveal space-y-6 font-body text-basalt/75 text-[16px] leading-relaxed" style="transition-delay: 0.1s;">
          <p>
            When the first basalt stones were laid at Nan Madol, Angkor Wat was a
            few decades old. Notre-Dame de Paris wasn't finished yet. The Incas
            hadn't yet built Machu Picchu. Easter Island's moai were still being
            carved. This was the medieval world — and out in the middle of the
            Pacific, Pohnpeians were building something no one else on Earth
            would ever attempt.
          </p>

          <p class="font-headline text-basalt text-lg italic">
            The numbers don't quite land until you see them in person:
          </p>

          <ul class="space-y-4 list-none">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre font-headline text-xl mt-0.5">—</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">92 artificial islets</strong>, laid out across 1.5 kilometers of lagoon</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre font-headline text-xl mt-0.5">—</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Basalt stones up to 50 tons each</strong>, moved from quarries on the far side of the island</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre font-headline text-xl mt-0.5">—</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Walls rising up to 25 feet high</strong>, stacked like log cabins in cross-hatched courses</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre font-headline text-xl mt-0.5">—</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Built over 400+ years</strong> by a society without metal tools, wheels, or draft animals</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p>
            How the stones were transported is still debated. How they were
            stacked is still debated. What's not debated is the scale. Nan Madol
            sits in the same conversation as Machu Picchu, Angkor Wat, and the
            great Egyptian tombs — megalithic feats built by pre-industrial
            societies that shouldn't, by any logic, have been possible.
          </p>
        </div>

        <p
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-xl md:text-2xl leading-snug mt-12 border-l-4 border-ochre pl-6"
          style="transition-delay: 0.2s;"
        >
          The difference: Machu Picchu gets a million visitors a year.
          Nan Madol gets a few hundred.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4. MID-PAGE CTA -->
    <section class="py-20 md:py-28 px-6 bg-basalt text-center">
      <div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="font-headline text-sand text-3xl md:text-4xl leading-[1.08] tracking-tight mb-4"
        >
          Start planning your trip to <em class="italic text-ochre">Pohnpei</em>.
        </h2>
        <p class="font-body text-sand/60 text-[15px] mb-8">
          A few days is enough to see the ruins. A week gets you the island.
        </p>
        <a
          href="/plan-your-trip"
          class="bg-ochre text-white px-8 py-4 font-label uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-xs font-semibold hover:bg-ochre-deep active:scale-95 transition-all inline-block"
        >
          Plan your visit →
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 5. WHAT YOU'LL SEE -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-10"
        >
          The main islet is <em class="italic text-ochre">Nandauwas</em>.
        </h2>

        <div class="reveal space-y-6 font-body text-basalt/75 text-[16px] leading-relaxed" style="transition-delay: 0.1s;">
          <p>
            It's the one in all the photos. A royal tomb complex, the most
            dramatic structure on the site, with outer walls 16 to 26 feet high.
            The stones are laid as crossed beams — long basalt columns stacked in
            alternating courses, held in place by their own weight. No mortar. No
            binding. Just the geometry of the stones.
          </p>

          <p>
            Walking through Nandauwas takes 30 to 45 minutes if you're moving
            steadily. An hour or more if you're taking photos.
          </p>

          <p>
            The rest of the 92 islets are spread across the lagoon, connected by
            tidal canals. Some you can reach on foot at low tide. Others are only
            accessible by boat, or by swimming. Much of the site sits
            underwater — the reef has risen (or the ocean has) over the last four
            centuries, and divers report seeing walls and platforms below the
            surface that never made it onto the maps.
          </p>

          <p class="italic text-basalt/60">
            Come expecting ruins in a living lagoon, not ruins behind velvet
            ropes. Mangrove roots grow through the walls. The tide comes in and
            goes out. It's a place, not an exhibit.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 6. HOW TO GET THERE -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand-deep">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-12"
        >
          Two ways in. Neither is <em class="italic text-ochre">effortless</em>.
        </h2>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-10">
          <div class="reveal bg-sand-bright border border-basalt/10 p-8" style="transition-delay: 0.1s;">
            <h3 class="font-headline text-xl text-basalt mb-1">By land</h3>
            <span class="font-label text-ochre tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[10px] font-semibold mb-4 block">Low Tide</span>
            <p class="font-body text-basalt/75 text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
              Nan Madol is about 90 minutes by car from Kolonia, in the
              Madolenihmw district on the southeast side of the island. Your
              hotel or a local taxi can arrange the drive — budget around
              $70–$80 for a round-trip taxi if you're not on a tour. From
              the parking area, a rough 10–15 minute footpath leads to the
              site. At the end of the path, you cross a shallow sea channel
              on foot. At low tide, the water is knee-deep. At high tide, it
              can reach your chest. Plan around the tides.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="reveal bg-sand-bright border border-basalt/10 p-8" style="transition-delay: 0.2s;">
            <h3 class="font-headline text-xl text-basalt mb-1">By boat</h3>
            <span class="font-label text-ochre tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[10px] font-semibold mb-4 block">High Tide</span>
            <p class="font-body text-basalt/75 text-[15px] leading-relaxed">
              A boat approach lets you enter the site the way the Saudeleur
              rulers did — through the canals, with the basalt walls rising
              from the water on either side. Boat tours can be arranged
              through the <strong class="text-basalt">Pohnpei Surf Club</strong>
              or through most hotels in Kolonia. Expect to pay $70–$100 per
              person for a guided tour.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="reveal font-body text-basalt/65 text-[15px] leading-relaxed max-w-3xl" style="transition-delay: 0.25s;">
          Both approaches are good. Most visitors prefer the boat for the view,
          and the walk for the cost. If you have the time, do both.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 7. WHAT TO BRING -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <div class="reveal bg-sand-bright border-2 border-basalt/10 p-8 md:p-12">
          <h2
            class="font-headline text-basalt text-2xl md:text-3xl leading-[1.08] tracking-tight mb-8"
          >
            Come prepared to get <em class="italic text-ochre">wet</em>.
          </h2>

          <ul class="space-y-5 font-body text-basalt/75 text-[15px] leading-relaxed list-none">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-0.5 font-semibold">✓</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Water shoes or sturdy sandals</strong> — you will wade through water and walk on wet rock</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-0.5 font-semibold">✓</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Clothes you don't mind soaking</strong> — swim shorts or quick-dry pants work</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-0.5 font-semibold">✓</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Cash in small bills</strong> — you'll pay small entry fees ($1–$5) in cash to the local landholders along the path. These are owed to the families who hold traditional rights to the land.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-0.5 font-semibold">✓</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Water and sunscreen</strong> — no shops at the site</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-0.5 font-semibold">✓</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">Insect repellent</strong> — mangroves mean mosquitoes</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-4">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-0.5 font-semibold">✓</span>
              <span><strong class="text-basalt">A waterproof bag</strong> — for your phone, camera, and anything else that shouldn't be swimming with you</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p class="font-body text-basalt/60 italic text-sm mt-8 leading-relaxed">
            A tide chart for Pohnpei is worth checking the morning of your visit.
            Low tide for walking, high tide for boat. Mid-tide can leave you
            splitting the difference.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 8. RESPECT -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand-deep">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-10"
        >
          Nan Madol is still <em class="italic text-ochre">sacred</em>.
        </h2>

        <div class="reveal space-y-6 font-body text-basalt/75 text-[16px] leading-relaxed" style="transition-delay: 0.1s;">
          <p>
            It's not a ruin in the abstract. The site is still managed under
            traditional Pohnpeian governance, and the families who live along the
            path are the ones who care for the land. The small entry fees go to
            them. A few things to keep in mind while you're there:
          </p>

          <ul class="space-y-3 list-none">
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-1">•</span>
              <span>Don't climb on the walls. Some of the stones shift.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-1">•</span>
              <span>Don't remove anything. Stones, coral, artifacts — all stay.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-1">•</span>
              <span>Some islets are off-limits. Your guide will tell you which. Follow their lead.</span>
            </li>
            <li class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-ochre mt-1">•</span>
              <span>Keep your voice down around the mortuary areas.</span>
            </li>
          </ul>

          <p class="italic text-basalt/60">
            Respect the site the way you would any sacred place — because that's
            what it is.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 9. IT'S ENDANGERED -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-10"
        >
          Listed on the World Heritage List <em class="italic text-ochre">in Danger</em>.
        </h2>

        <div class="reveal space-y-6 font-body text-basalt/75 text-[16px] leading-relaxed" style="transition-delay: 0.1s;">
          <p>
            UNESCO inscribed Nan Madol in 2016 — and placed it on the World
            Heritage List in Danger the same day. Mangrove roots are dislodging
            stones. Canals are silting up. Typhoons move walls that have stood
            for 800 years. Sea level rise is slow but real.
          </p>

          <p class="italic text-basalt/60">
            Preservation efforts are underway. But the site is fragile, and it's
            the kind of fragile that can't be undone. If you're coming, come
            soon, and come carefully.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 10. PAIR THIS WITH -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand-bright">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-4"
        >
          Make a <em class="italic text-ochre">day</em> of it.
        </h2>
        <p class="reveal font-body text-basalt/65 text-[15px] leading-relaxed mb-12" style="transition-delay: 0.08s;">
          Nan Madol is on the southeast side of the island. A few things to
          consider adding to the trip:
        </p>

        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          <a
            href="/waterfalls-and-jungle"
            class="reveal group bg-sand border border-basalt/10 p-6 flex flex-col transition-colors hover:border-ochre/30"
            style="transition-delay: 0.12s;"
          >
            <span class="font-label text-ochre tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[10px] font-semibold mb-3 block">
              Kepirohi Falls
            </span>
            <p class="font-body text-basalt/70 text-sm leading-relaxed flex-grow">
              A short detour on the way back to Kolonia. An easy hike to a wide
              waterfall with a swimmable pool at the base. Cleans the salt off
              after Nan Madol.
            </p>
            <span class="text-ochre font-body text-sm mt-4 group-hover:translate-x-1 transition-transform inline-block">→</span>
          </a>

          <a
            href="/diving-and-surfing"
            class="reveal group bg-sand border border-basalt/10 p-6 flex flex-col transition-colors hover:border-ochre/30"
            style="transition-delay: 0.2s;"
          >
            <span class="font-label text-ochre tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[10px] font-semibold mb-3 block">
              Dive the submerged portions
            </span>
            <p class="font-body text-basalt/70 text-sm leading-relaxed flex-grow">
              Experienced divers can arrange access to the underwater sections
              of the site. Walls, platforms, and structures that never made it
              into guidebooks.
            </p>
            <span class="text-ochre font-body text-sm mt-4 group-hover:translate-x-1 transition-transform inline-block">→</span>
          </a>

          <a
            href="/waterfalls-and-jungle"
            class="reveal group bg-sand border border-basalt/10 p-6 flex flex-col transition-colors hover:border-ochre/30"
            style="transition-delay: 0.28s;"
          >
            <span class="font-label text-ochre tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-[10px] font-semibold mb-3 block">
              Madolenihmw Bay
            </span>
            <p class="font-body text-basalt/70 text-sm leading-relaxed flex-grow">
              The wider area around Nan Madol is worth exploring. Paddling,
              snorkeling, and the towering Takaiuh ("standing rock") across
              the bay.
            </p>
            <span class="text-ochre font-body text-sm mt-4 group-hover:translate-x-1 transition-transform inline-block">→</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 11. FINAL CTA -->
    <section class="py-28 md:py-36 px-6 md:px-24 bg-sand">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h2
          class="reveal font-headline text-basalt text-3xl md:text-4xl lg:text-5xl leading-[1.05] tracking-tight mb-6"
        >
          Ready to <em class="italic text-ochre">go</em>?
        </h2>
        <p class="reveal font-body text-basalt/70 text-[16px] leading-relaxed mb-10 max-w-xl mx-auto" style="transition-delay: 0.1s;">
          Nan Madol is one of the most extraordinary sites you'll ever visit.
          It's also one of the least crowded. Plan your trip and we'll help you
          put the days together.
        </p>
        <a
          href="/plan-your-trip"
          class="reveal bg-ochre text-white px-8 py-4 font-label uppercase tracking-[0.14em] text-xs font-semibold hover:bg-ochre-deep active:scale-95 transition-all inline-block"
          style="transition-delay: 0.15s;"
        >
          Start planning your trip →
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>

  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
